Proto-Proposal
---
Currency Market

 Enact a Rule, titled "Agoran Monetary Standard", reading :

   At any time, exactly one Currency shall be designated as Agora's 
   Reference Currency. The Reference Currency may be designated by 
   the Rules, or any other means specified in the Rules.

   If the Rules fail to directly or indirectly specify a Reference 
   Currency, Voting Tokens shall be designated as the Reference 
   Currency.

   The Chancellor shall keep track of which Currency is the Reference 
   Currency, and post this information whenever e posts a list of 
   existing Currencies.

 Enact a Rule, titled "Exchange Rates", reading :

   Each Currency shall have associated with it an Exchange Rate, 
   which shall consist of a multiple of the MUQ of that Currency and 
   a multiple of the MUQ of the Currency currently designated as the 
   Reference Currency.

   The Exchange Rate of the Reference Currency shall at all times be 
   one to one.

   If the Rules fail to directly or indirectly specify a Currency's 
   Exchange Rate, that Currency shall have an Exchange Rate of zero 
   to one. A Currency with an Exchange Rate other than zero to one is 
   called a Traded Currency.

   The Chancellor shall keep track of the Exchange Rates of all
   Currencies, and post this information whenever e posts a list of
   existing Currencies.

 Enact a Rule, titled "Exchange Offers", reading :

   An Exchange Offer is a statement posted to the Public Forum 
   whereby a Player agrees to transfer an amount of a Currency called 
   the Sold Quantity to any Player who agrees to transfer to em an 
   amount of a different Currency known as the Purchase Price.

   Both Sold Quantity and Purchase Price must be expressed in 
   multiples of the MUQ of their respectives Currencies; further, the 
   Sold Quantity shall not exceed the amount of the relevant Currency 
   owned by the Player making the Offer, nor shall the Purchase Price 
   exceed the largest amount of the relevant Currency owned by any 
   Player. No Exchange Offer shall be valid unless it meets these 
   criteria.

   A Player who posts an Exchange Offer is bound to honor that 
   agreement with the first Player who announces that e is willing
   to perform the Exchange, and no other Player, within one Week of 
   entering the agreement.

   Fair and appropriate compensation for the breach of an agreement 
   entered into as the result of taking up an Exchange Offer, by 
   either party, shall consist of the amounts named therein plus a 
   penalty of 10% for the party responsible for the breach.

 Enact a Rule, titled "Exchange Rate Computation", reading :

   The Chancellor shall have the authority to compute the Exchange 
   Rate of any Currency.

   This consists of averaging the Sold Quantities of the Currency being
   considered and Purchase Prices naming the Reference Currency in
   Exchange Offers that have been posted since the last time that
   Exchange Rate was computed. The result is the Temporary Exchange
   Rate for that Currency. If no such Exchange Offers have been posted
   since the last computation, the Temporary Exchange Rate shall be the
   same as the last computed Exchange Rate.

   The Reference Currency equivalents in Purchase Prices of any other
   Currencies, computed at the Temporary Exchange Rate, and the Sold
   Quantities of the Currency being considered in all Exchange Offers 
   posted since the last computation shall be averaged to derive the 
   new Exchange Rate for that Currency.

   The Chancellor shall compute a new Exchange Rate for all 
   Currencies no more frequently than once a Week and no less than 
   once a Month.

   Whenever the Reference Currency is changed, the Chancellor shall 
   compute new Exchange Rates for all Currencies, such that the 
   same amount of a Currency is equivalent to the same amount of the 
   new Reference Currency.
---

[This is an attempt, possibly feeble, at introducing the notion of
determining the market values of Currencies with respect to each
other, which would make custom Currencies much more interesting. Any
comments, suggestions or improvements welcomed, especially as do not
have the faintest notion how such things are done in the Real
World.]

